{"parse":{"title":"apple","pageid":2154,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Apple|äpple}}\n==English==\n{{was wotd|2024|October|21}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|id=fruit|:inh|enm:appel<id:apple>|tree=1}}\n{{multiple images\n| direction = vertical\n| image1   = Red Apple.jpg\n| caption1 = An apple ({{senseno|en|Q89}}).\n| image2   = Apple Blossom Time at Oak Glen, CA 3-16 (26094251756).jpg\n| caption2 = An apple ({{senseno|en|apple tree}}) or [[apple tree]] in [[blossom#Noun|blossom]].\n| image3   = Frans Floris - The Fall of Man - Google Art Project.jpg\n| caption3 = ''{{w|The Fall of Man}}'' ({{circa2|1560|short=1}}) by {{w|Frans Floris}},{{ref|group=n|name=n1|From the collection of the {{w|Malmö Art Museum}} in [[Malmö]], [[Scania]], [[Sweden]].}} which depicts [[Adam and Eve]] in the [[Garden of Eden]] with apples ({{senseno|en|forbidden fruit}}) or [[forbidden fruit]].\n}}\n\nThe {{glossary|noun}} is derived from {{inh|en|enm|appel|t=''Malus domestica'' fruit or tree, apple; any type of fruit, nut, or tuber; tree bearing fruit; (''figurative'') ball, sphere; (''Christianity'') forbidden fruit in Eden}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=appel|pos=n|id=MED1901}}</ref> from {{inh|en|ang|æppel|t=apple; any type of fruit; (''figurative'') ball, sphere; eyeball}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*applu|t=apple; any type of fruit}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*aplaz|t=apple; any type of fruit}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂ébōl}}, {{m|ine-pro|*h₂ébl̥|t=apple}}.<ref name=\"OED\">{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=1190710016|date=September 2024|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref>\n\nAs regards {{senseno|en|forbidden fruit|t=forbidden fruit}}, the type of fruit eaten by Adam and Eve is not identified in the {{w|Book of Genesis}} in the [[Bible]]. It may have come to be identified with the apple because of the similarity between {{noncog|la|mālum|t=apple}} and {{m|la|malum|t=evil; misery, torment; wrongdoing}}.<ref name=\"OED\"/>\n\nThe {{glossary|verb}} is derived from the noun.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=v|id=9926648781|date=June 2024}}</ref>\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|aipple|t=apple}}, {{cog|frr|aapel}}, {{m|frr|Oapel}}, {{m|frr|ååpel|t=apple}}, {{cog|stq|Apel}}, {{m|stq|Appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|fy|apel}}, {{m|fy|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|gsw|effél}}, {{m|gsw|epfel}}, {{m|gsw|epfil}}, {{m|gsw|öpfil|t=apple}}, {{cog|bar|eipfele}}, {{m|bar|epfl}}, {{m|bar|Åpfe|t=apple}}, {{cog|cim|oupfal}}, {{m|cim|öpfel}}, {{m|cim|öpfl|t=apple}}, {{cog|nl|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|de|Apfel|t=apple}}, {{cog|nds-de|Appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|li|Ape̩l}}, {{m|li|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|lb|Apel|t=apple}}, {{cog|mhn|epfl|t=apple}}, {{cog|wym|epuł|t=apple}}, {{cog|yi|עפּל|t=apple}}, {{cog|da|æble|t=apple}}, {{cog|fo|epl}}, {{m|fo|epli|t=apple; potato}}, {{cog|is|epli|t=apple}}, {{cog|nb,nn|eple|t=apple}}, {{cog|sv|äpple|t=apple}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|apel|t=apple}}, {{cog|ga|úll|t=apple}}, {{cog|lt|óbuolỹs|t=apple}}, {{cog|ru|я́блоко|t=apple}}, {{cog|cy|afal|t=apple}}, possibly {{cog|grc|ἄμπελος|t=vine}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈæpəl/|[ˈæpəl]|~|[ˈæpl̩]}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-apple.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-apple.ogg|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-apple.wav|a=Southern England}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-apple.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈæ.pɘl/|/ˈa.pɘl/|a=Indic}}\n:: the final L might be retroflexed; compare Malayalam [[ആപ്പിൾ]].\n* {{rhymes|en|æpəl|s=2}}\n* {{hyph|en|ap|ple}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[common#Adjective|common]], [[firm#Adjective|firm]], [[round#Adjective|round]] [[fruit#Noun|fruit]] [[produce#Verb|produced]] by a [[tree#Noun|tree]] of the [[genus]] {{taxfmt|Malus|genus}}.\n#: {{hypernyms|en|fruit|hand fruit|pome}}\n## {{senseid|en|Q89}} The fruit of the tree {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}}, chiefly with a [[green#Adjective|green]], [[red#Adjective|red]], or [[yellow#Adjective|yellow]] [[skin#Noun|skin]], [[cultivate]]d in [[temperate#Adjective|temperate]] [[climate#Noun|climates]] for [[cidermaking]], [[cooking#Noun|cooking]], and [[eating#Noun|eating]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Elyot Castel of Helth|chapter=Of Apples|folio=21|passage=All '''apples''' eaten ſoone after y&#877; they be gathered, are cold, hard to digeſt, and do make ill and corrupted bloud, but being wel kept vntill y&#868; next winter, or the year folowing, eatẽ {{quote-gloss|eaten}} after meales, they are right holeſome, & doe confyrme the ſtomacke, & make good digeſtion, ſpecially if they be roſted or baked, {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=VI|chapter=The Arij, and Other Nations Depending unto Them|page=128|passage=[T]hey {{quote-gloss|''i.e.'', writers}} aſſigne and lay to India, the countrey of the Aſpagores, ſo plentifull in vines, laurels, and box, and generally of all ſorts of '''apple''' trees and other fruitfull trees that grovv vvithin Greece.}}\n##* {{RQ:Bunyan Pilgrim's Progress|page=233|passage=VVhat of my ''droſs'' thou findeſt there, be bold / To throvv avvay, but yet preserve the Gold. / VVhat if my Gold be vvrapped up in Ore? / None throvvs avvay the '''Apple''' for the Core.}}\n##* {{RQ:Spectator|author=Steele|issue=509|date=14 October 1712|page=501|passage=Instead of the assembly of honourable merchants, substantial tradesmen, and knowing masters of ships; the mumpers, the halt, the blind, and the lame; your venders of trash, '''apples''', plums; your ragamuffins, rakeshames, and wenches; have justled the greater number of the former out of that place.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Emma|volume=I|chapter=IX|pages=184–185|pageref=185|passage=I have so often heard Mr. Woodhouse recommend a baked '''apple'''. I believe it is the only way that Mr. Woodhouse thinks the fruit thoroughly wholesome. We have '''apple''' dumplings, however, very often. Patty makes an excellent '''apple'''-dumpling.}}\n##* {{RQ:Lawrence Phoenix|title=Flowery Tuscany|section=III|page=52|passage=This red seems to me the perfect premonition of summer—like the red on the outside of '''apple''' blossom—and later, the red of the '''apple'''. It is the premonition in redness of summer and of autumn.}}\n##* {{RQ:Guardian|date=28 October 2013|author=John Vallins|title=Apples of Concord|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20230923080841/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/28/somerset-apples-of-concord|passage=Close by and under cover, I watched the juicing process. '''Apples''' were washed, then tipped, stalks and all, into the crusher and reduced to pulp.}}\n## ''Often with a [[qualify]]ing [[word#Noun|word]]'': any fruit or [[vegetable#Noun|vegetable]], or any other [[thing]] (such as a [[cone#Noun|cone]] or [[gall#Noun|gall]]) produced by a [[plant#Noun|plant]], especially if from a tree and similar to the fruit of {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}} ''({{senseno|en|Q89}})''. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##: {{coi|en|[[custard apple|custard '''apple''']]&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; [[rose apple|rose '''apple''']]&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; [[thorn apple|thorn '''apple''']]}}\n##* {{RQ:d'Anghiera Eden Newe Worlde|chapter=Weste Indies|subchapter=Of Venemous Apples wherwith They Poyson Theyr Arrowes|folio=198|verso=1|passage=The '''apples''' wherewith the Indian Canibales inueneme theyr arrowes, growe on certeyne trees couered with many braunches and leaues beinge very greene and growyng thicke. They are laden with abundaunce of theſe euyll frutes, {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Gerard Herball|chapter=Of the Pine Tree|page=1174|passage=This '''apple''' is called in high Dutch, Zyꝛbel {{quote-gloss|Zyrbel}}: in low Dutch, Pijn appel: in Engliſh, Pine apple, Clogge, and Cone. {{...}} The vvhole Cone or '''apple''' being boiled vvith freſh Horehound, ſaith ''{{w|Galen}}'', and aftervvards boyled againe vvith a little hony till the decoction be come to the thicknes of hony, maketh an excellent medicine for the clenſing of the cheſt and lungs.}}\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=XI|chapter=The Trees of the Iland Tyles within the Persian Sea. Moreover, of Those Trees that Beare Woll or Cotton.|page=364|passage=As touching Arabia, vvhich lyeth neere and bordereth upon theſe Iſlands, the ſpices and odoriferous fruits that be therein, are to be treated of vvith diſtinction: for their merchandiſe doth conſiſt of roots, braunches, barke, juice or liquor, gums and roſins, vvood, tvvigs, flovvers, leaves, and '''apple'''.}}\n##* {{RQ:Topsell Foure-footed Beastes|chapter=IX|page=666|passage=The fruite or '''Apples''' of Palme-trees (eſpecially ſuch as grovv in ſalt grounds neare the Sea ſides, as in ''Cyrene'' of ''Affrica'', and ''Indea'', and not in ''Egypt'', ''Cyprus'', ''Syria'', ''Helvetia'', and ''Aſsiria'' do fatten and feed Hogges.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1658|author=John Baptista Porta [''i.e.'', {{w|Giambattista della Porta}}]|chapter=That the Countries and Places where Simples Grow, are Chiefly to be Considered|translator=[anonymous]|title=[[w:Magia Naturalis|Natural Magick {{...|by John Baptista Porta, a Neopolitane. In Twenty Books [...]}} Wherein are Set Forth All the Riches and Delights of the Natural Sciences]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} John Wright,{{nb...|next to the sign of the Globe in Little-Britain.}}|year_published=1669|section=1st book (Wherein are Searched Out the Causes of Things which Produce Wonderful Effects)|page=21|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WddkXA6n51UC&pg=PA21|oclc=458053876|passage=In Perſia there grovvs a deadly tree, vvhoſe '''apples''' are poiſon, and preſent death: therefore there it is uſed for a puniſhment: but being brought over to the Kings into Egypt, they become vvholeſome '''apples''' to eat, and loſe their harmfulneſſe, as ''{{w|Columella}}'' vvrites.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1768|author=Edward Search [pseudonym; {{w|Abraham Tucker}}]|chapter=External Nature|title=The Light of Nature Pursued|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} T. Jones,{{nb...|in Fetter-Lane}}; and sold by [[w:Thomas Payne|T[homas] Payne]],{{nb...|at the Mews-Gate.}}|volume=!II, part I (Theology)|section=paragraph 13|page=302|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=U_5NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA302|oclc=1326256104|passage=[T]he fly injects her juices into the oak leaf to raiſe an '''apple''' for hatching her young and therein ſupplies us vvith ink for our correſpondence and improvement.}}\n##* {{RQ:Cook King Voyage|volume=II|chapter=IX|page=174|passage=[I]t {{quote-gloss|Otaheite}} is remarkable for producing great quantities of that delicious fruit we called '''apples''', which are found in none of the others, except Eimeo.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1825|author=w:Theodric Romeyn Beck; William Dunlop|title=Elements of Medical Jurisprudence.{{nb...|[...] Second Edition, with Notes, and an Appendix of Original Cases and the Latest Discoveries. By William Dunlop, Member of the Royal College of Surgeons, London; of the Medico-Chirurgical, and of the Wernerian Society of Natural History, Edinburgh; and Lecturer on Medical Jurisprudence, &c. &c.}}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} John Anderson,{{nb...|medical bookseller, West-Smithfield}}|page=565|oclc=1012791003|passage=''Hippomane mancinella.'' (Manchineel-tree.) Dr. Peysonnel relates that a soldier, who was a slave with the Turks, eat some of the '''apples''' of this tree, and was soon seized with a swelling and pain of the abdomen.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1829|author=&#91;{{w|John Leonard Knapp}}&#93;|title=The Journal of a Naturalist|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=[[w:John Murray (publishing house)|John Murray]],{{nb...|Albemarle-Street.}}|pages=250–251|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9XdJAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA250|oclc=17661598|passage=The cross-bill will have seeds from the '''apple''', or cone of the fir—the green-finch, seeds from the uplands, or door of barn, or rickyard.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1833|author=Charles Williams|chapter=The Aged Tree|title=The Vegetable World|location=London|publisher=Frederick Westley and [[w:Abraham Hopkins Davis|A[braham] H[opkins] Davis]],{{nb...|Stationers’-Hall Court.}}|page=192|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_6RgAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA192|oclc=18038938|passage=One kind of '''apple''' or gall, inhabited only by one grub, is hard and woody on the outside, resembling a little wooden ball, of a yellowish color, but internally it is of a soft, spongy texture.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1889|author=B. D. Halstead<!--See p. 336-->|title=Report of the Section of Vegetable Pathology [9.—Apple Rusts.]|journal=Report of the [[w:United States Secretary of Agriculture|Commissioner of Agriculture]]. 1888|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|page=376|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0hVFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA376|oclc=942757499|passage=The \"'''apple'''\" or gall usually forms a somewhat kidney-shaped excrescence, attached by a small base on the concave side, and varying in size from a half an inch to an inch and a half in length.}}\n## Something which [[resemble]]s the fruit of {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}} ''({{senseno|en|Q89}})'' in [[shape#Noun|shape]] (such as a [[ball#Noun|ball]], [[breast#Noun|breast]], or [[globe#Noun|globe]]) or [[color#Noun|colour]].\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=2|book=XXXVI|chapter=The First Invention of Glasse, and the Manner of Making It. Of a Kind of Glasse, Called Obsidianum. Also of Sundrie Kinds of Glasse, and Those of Manie Formes.|page=598|passage=[H]old a round ball or hollovv '''apple''' of glaſſe full of vvater againſt the Sunne, it vvill be ſo hot, that it is ready to burne any cloth that it toucheth.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1705|author=J. S.|chapter=The Ways and Artifices of a Town-jilt, &c.|title=City and Country Recreation: Or, Wit and Merriment Rightly Calculated, for the Pleasure and Advantage of Either Sex.{{nb...|In Two Parts. [...] To which is Added, The Misery of Gaming: Or The Art of Keeping Ready Money in One’s Pocket at All Times: With Other Useful Matters, never before Made Publick.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} W. O. for P. Parker,{{nb...|at the Leg and Star in Cornhil}}|section=2nd part|page=104|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7lcAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA104|oclc=1325795882|passage=[S]hrugging up her Shoulders, to ſhevv the tempting '''Apples''' of her vvhite Breaſts, ſhe ſuddainly lets them ſink again, to hide them, bluſhing, as if this had been done by chance, {{...}}}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1761|chapter=Of the Order of the Procession of the Electoral Princes, and of Those who are to Carry the Honorary Ensigns|title=The Modern Part of an Universal History, from the Earliest Account of Time.{{nb...|Compiled from Original Writers. By the Authors of the Antient Part.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} [[w:Samuel Richardson|S[amuel] Richardson]],{{nb...|T[homas] Osborne, C. Hitch, A[ndrew] Millar, John Rivington, S. Crowder, B. Law and Co. T[homas] Longman and C. Ware.}}|volume=XXX|page=508|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ONjh-Aat5ZYC&pg=PA508|oclc=1180917051|passage=[T]he ſaid elector of ''Saxony'' ſhall have on his right the count-palatine of the ''Rhine'', vvho ſhall carry the globe or imperial '''apple'''; and, on his left, the marquis of ''Brandenburg'' carrying the ſcepter.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1807|author=w:Sharon Turner|chapter=The Political State of Norway, Sweden, and Denmark, in the Eighth Century|title=The History of the Anglo-Saxons.{{nb...|[...] Second Edition, Corrected and Enlarged.}}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} [[w:Longman|Longman, Hurst, Rees, & Orme]],{{nb...|Paternoster Row.}}|volume=I|section=book III, footnote 20|page=200|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=O2AOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA200|column=2|oclc=1018396940|passage=The arms of Upland were a golden '''apple''', or globe, surrounded with a belt, in allusion to the monarchy.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1956|author=w:Marion Hargrove|title=The Girl He Left Behind: Or, All Quiet in the Third Platoon|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Viking Books|page=129|oclc=1336143924|passage=Andy picked up his two grenades and followed the line into the pits. The '''apples''' felt strangely heavy in his hands, and when he looked at them one was as ugly and lethal-looking as the other.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1975|author=[[w:C. W. Smith (writer)|C[harles] W[illiam] Smith]]|chapter=IX|title=Country Music|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Farrar, Straus and Giroux|page=256|isbn=978-0-374-13030-5|passage=A peasant blouse that showed the tops of those lovely little '''apples'''.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=w:Harald Kleinschmidt|title=Ruling the Waves: Emperor Maximilian I, the Search for Islands and the Transformation of the European World Picture c. 1500|series=Bibliotheca Humanistica & Reformatorica|seriesvolume=63|location=’t Goy, Houten, Utrecht|publisher=Hes & de Graaf Publishers|page=79|isbn=978-90-6194-020-3|issn=1567-8385|passage=Contrary to [[w:Henricus Martellus Germanus|Henricus Martellus {{quote-gloss|Germanus}}]], [[w:Martin Behaim|{{quote-gloss|Martin}} Behaim]] included the tropics {{quote-gloss|on his globe}}. {{...}} Evidently, there was no space for a Fourth Continent on Behaim's '''apple''', although some recollection of the Catalan map seems to lie behind the shape of southern Africa.}}\n### {{ellipsis of|en|Adam's apple|t=the lump in the throat, usually more [[noticeable]] in men than in women; the [[laryngeal prominence]]}}.\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=1898|author=[[w:Hugh Clifford (colonial administrator)|Hugh [Charles] Clifford]]|chapter=In Arcadia|title=Studies in Brown Humanity: Being Scrawls and Smudges in Sepia, White, and Yellow|location=London|publisher=[[w:Grant Richards (publisher)|Grant Richards]]{{nb...|9 Henrietta Street, Covent Garden, W.C.}}|page=99|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/studiesinbrownhu00clif/page/99/mode/1up|oclc=2059083|passage=The sweat of fear and exertion was streaming down his face and chest, and his breath came in short, tearing, hard-drawn gasps and gulps, while the '''apple''' in his throat leaped up and down ceaselessly like a ball balanced on a dancing jet of water.}}\n###* {{RQ:Williamson Dandelion Days|chapter=Formation of the Owl Club|pages=113–114|pageref=113|passage=Elsie went away with her parents to Belgium and the convent-school on the twelfth, and as they left The Firs in the battered station cab surrounded by boxes and trunks, Willie could not speak. The '''apple''' in his throat rose and remained there.}}\n###* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|page=234|passage=He looked with vague hope up and down the quay, a big '''apple''' bulging in his neck.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=a. '''1985''' (date written)<!--year after author's death-->|author=[[w:Liam O'Flaherty|Liam O’Flaherty]]|chapter=Josephine|editor=A[ngeline] A. Kelly|title=The Collected Stories|volume=1|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Palgrave Macmillan|year_published=1999|page=131|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbUYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|isbn=978-1-349-62699-1|passage=The '''apple''' in his neck was hitting against his collar every time he drew breath and he tore at his collar nervously.}}\n###* {{RQ:Martin Storm of Swords|page=846|passage=If the Hound had not been moving, the knife might have cored the '''apple''' of his throat; instead it only grazed his ribs, and wound up quivering in the wall near the door. He laughed then, a laugh as cold and hollow as if it had come from the bottom of a deep well.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=[[w:Sandra Benitez|Sandra Benítez]]|chapter=|title=Night of the Radishes|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Hachette Books|Hyperion]]|page=223|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/nightofradishes00ben/page/223/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-7868-6400-3|passage=The '''apple''' in his neck bobbles as he gulps. “You've got to be kidding.” / “No, I'm not. Your inheritance amounts to maybe three hundred thousand dollars.\"}}\n### {{ellipsis of|en|apple-green|t=a bright green colour with a light tint of yellow, like that of a [[Granny Smith]] apple}}.\n###: {{color panel|7FD700}}\n### {{lb|en|historical}} {{ellipsis of|en|apple of the eye|t=the [[pupil]], or pupil and iris, of the eye, originally [[believe]]d to be [[spherical]]; also, the eyeball}}.\n###* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=XI|chapter=A Discourse Anatomicall, of the Nature of Living Creatures, Part by Part, according to Their Particular Members|page=334|passage=None have their eies all of one colour: for the ball or '''apple''' in the middeſt is ordinarily of another colour than the vvhite about it.}}\n###* {{RQ:Homer Chapman Iliads|book=XIV|pages=197–198|pageref=198|passage=The dart did vndergore / His eye-lid, by his eyes deare rootes; and out the '''apple''' fell, / The eye pierc'd through: {{...}}}}\n### {{lb|en|informal}} The round, [[fleshy]] [[part#Noun|part]] of a [[cheek#Noun|cheek]] between the eye and the [[corner#Noun|corner]] of the [[mouth#Noun|mouth]] when a [[person#Noun|person]] is [[smile#Verb|smiling]].\n### {{senseid|en|geometry}}{{lb|en|geometry}} The [[surface of revolution]] of a [[circular arc]] of an [[angle#Noun|angle]] [[great#Adjective|greater]] than 180° [[rotate#Verb|rotated]] about the [[straight line]] [[pass#Verb|passing]] through the [[arc#Noun|arc]]'s two [[endpoint]]s.\n###: {{cot|en|{{l|en|lemon|id=geometry}}}}\n### {{lb|en|smoking}} ''In full'' '''apple bowl''': a round [[bowl#Noun|bowl]] of a [[tobacco pipe]]; also, a tobacco pipe with such a bowl.\n### {{lb|en|obsolete|baseball|slang}} ''In full'' '''old apple''': a [[baseball]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}\n###* {{quote-av|en|date=25 February 1990|writers=w:Matt Groening; w:Al Jean; w:Mike Reiss; w:Sam Simon|episode=w:The Telltale Head|title=w:The Simpsons|season=1|number=8|passage=Hey Dad! What do you say we toss the old '''apple''' around, huh? Sound like fun?}}\n## {{senseid|en|forbidden fruit}}{{lb|en|Christianity}} According to [[postbiblical]] [[Christian#Adjective|Christian]] [[tradition#Noun|tradition]], the fruit of the [[tree of knowledge]] which was [[eat#Verb|eaten]] by [[Adam and Eve]] despite [[God]] [[command#Verb|commanding]] them not to do so; the [[forbidden fruit]]. {{defdate|from 11th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=IX|sig=&#91;Ll4&#93;|page=272|lines=485–487|passage=Him {{quote-gloss|man}} by fraud I {{quote-gloss|{{w|Satan}}}} have ſeduc'd / From his Creator, and the more to increaſe / Your vvonder, vvith an '''Apple'''; {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Mary Shelley Frankenstein|volume=III|page=102|passage=I read and re-read her letter, and some softened feelings stole into my heart, and dared to whisper paradisiacal dreams of love and joy; but the '''apple''' was already eaten, and the angel's arm bared to drive me from all hope.}}\n##* {{RQ:Southey All for Love|page=20|passage=Yes, of all human follies, love, / Methinks, hath served me best. / The '''Apple''' had done but little for me / If {{w|Eve}} had not done the rest.}}\n##* {{RQ:Stowe My Wife and I|chapter=Congratulations, etc.|page=399|passage=Yes, fair Eve, just as {{w|Adam}} ate the '''apple''', so beware!}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year='''1975''' (date written)|author=w:Barry Reckord|chapter=White Witch|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=84oHEAAAQBAJ&pg=PT209|title=For the Reckord: A Collection of Three Plays|location=London|publisher=w:Oberon Books|year_published=2010|isbn=978-1-84943-053-1|passage=Yes mam. Woman ate the '''apple''', and discovered sex, and lost all shame, and lift{{sic}} up her fig-leaf, and she must suffer the pains of hell. Monthly.}}\n##* {{quote-song|en|year=1976|author=w:Joni Mitchell|title=Song for Sharon|album=[[w:Hejira (album)|Hejira]]|location=Los Angeles, Calif.|publisher=w:Asylum Records|oclc=939485378|passage=Sharon you've got a husband / And a family and a farm / I've got the '''apple''' of temptation / And a diamond snake around my arm}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete|botany}} {{synonym of|en|pome|t=a [[type#Noun|type]] of fruit in which the often [[edible#Adjective|edible]] [[flesh#Noun|flesh]] [[arise#Verb|arises]] from the [[swollen#Adjective|swollen]] [[base#Noun|base]] of the [[flower#Noun|flower]] and not from the [[carpel]]s}}.\n## {{lb|en|internet slang|humorous}} An imaginary [[diminutive]] unit of [[height]].\n##: {{ux|en|He's only three '''apples''' tall}}\n# {{senseid|en|apple tree}} A tree of the genus ''Malus''; especially {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}} which is cultivated for its edible fruit; the [[apple tree]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}\n#: {{synonyms|en|malus}}\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Sylva Sylvarum|chapter=Experiments in Consort, Touching the Lasting of Herbs and Trees|page=146|para=584|passage=''Trees'' that beare ''Maſt'', and ''Nuts'', are commonly more laſting, than thoſe that beare ''Fruits''; Eſpecially the ''Moiſter Fruits'': As ''Oakes'', ''Beeches'', ''Cheſ-nuts'', ''VVall-nuts'', ''Almonds'', ''Pine-Trees'', &c. laſt longer than '''''Apples''''', ''Peares'', ''Plums'', &c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|chapter=The Science of Plant Growing|editor=John Weathers|title=Commercial Gardening{{nb...|A Practical & Scientific Treatise for Market Gardeners, Market Growers, Fruit Flower & Vegetable Growers, Nurserymen etc. [...] In Four Volumes: Fully Illustrated}}|location=London|publisher=The Gresham Publishing Company{{nb...|34–35 Southampton Street Strand London}}|volume=I|section=§4 (The Root and Its Work)|page=38|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/commercialgarden0001john/page/38/mode/1up|oclc=2485680|passage=If the grafted portion of an '''Apple''' or other tree were examined after one hundred years, the old cut surfaces would still be present, for mature or ripened wood, being dead, never unites.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Peter Thomas|chapter=The Next Generation: New Trees from Old|title=Trees: Their Natural History|location=Cambridge, Cambridgeshire|publisher=w:Cambridge University Press|year_published=2001|page=227|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/treestheirnatura0000thom_s4l2/page/227/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-521-45351-6|passage=This allows a weak plant to benefit from the strong roots of another, or a vigorous tree (such as an '''apple''') to be kept small by growing on 'dwarfing rootstock'.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|author=Sid Gardner|title=The Faults of the Owens Valley|location=Bloomington, Ind.|publisher=w:iUniverse|page=34|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=gcbQzBOnc0YC&pg=PA34|isbn=978-1-4401-7793-4|passage=Used to be apple orchards, used to be the river and irrigation ditches that watered the '''apples''', used to be mining towns.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=Terri Reid|chapter=Starting an Orchard|title=The Everything Guide to Living Off the Grid: A Back-to-basics Manual for Independent Living|series=Everything Series|location=Avon, Mass.|publisher=Adams Media, [[w:F+W|F+W Media]]|page=77|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQrtDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT78|isbn=978-1-4405-1275-9|passage=Some fruit trees, like plums, do well in damp soil conditions. Other fruit trees, like '''apples''', need well-drained soil.}}\n# {{synonym of|en|applewood|t=the [[wood#Noun|wood]] of the [[apple tree]]}}. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n# {{lb|en|puristic|otherwise|obsolete}} A fruit of any kind.\n# {{lb|en|by extension|slang}}\n## {{lb|en|often|with qualifying word}} A [[person]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1928|year_published=1984|author=S.J. Perelman|chapter=Phantoms of the Dawn|title=That Old gang o' Mine: The Early and Essential S.J. Perelman|page=43|text=“I saw a little guy with a can opener fooling around that gum machine,” was the reply.<br />“And then?” asked McGonigle.<br />“I can’t say,” replied the poor '''apple'''.|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/thatoldgangomine00pere/page/43/}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1948|month=April|author=John C. Ropke|title=You Can’t Stay On Top|journal=Masked Rider Western|page=64|text=“Take it easy with Thompson, Eddie,” he said lazily. “He’s a good '''apple''' but he’s mighty tough to go pushing around. He’s had a lot of bad luck lately.”|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/masked-rider-western-v-23-n-03-1948-04/page/64/}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1963|author=H.E. Bates|title=Oh! To Be in England|page=20|text=Pop delighted in calling his grandson Blenheim; it was such a nice round apple of a name.<br />‘Well, how’s Charley boy? And how’s my little '''apple'''?’|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/ohtobeinengland0000heba/page/20/}}\n## {{lb|en|amateur radio}} {{synonym of|en|CBer|t=a [[CB radio]] [[enthusiast]]}}.\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1977|author=|title=|editor=w:Bernard Dixon|journal=w:New Scientist|location=London|publisher=[[w:TI Media#International Publishing Corporation|IPC Magazines]]|volume=74|page=764|column=1|passage=Because of overcrowding, many a CB enthusiast (called an \"'''apple'''\") is strapping an illegal linear amplifier (\"boots\") on to his transceiver (\"ears\") which is limited by the Federal Communications Commission (\"Big Daddy\" in the US) to an output power of no more than five watts.}}\n## {{lb|en|ice hockey}} An [[assist#Noun|assist]].\n## {{lb|en|US|derogatory|ethnic slur}} A [[Native American#Adjective|Native American]] or [[redskinned]] person who [[act#Verb|acts]] or [[think#Verb|thinks]] like a [[white#Adjective|white]] ([[Caucasian#Adjective|Caucasian]]) person.\n##: {{coordinate terms|en|banana|coconut|Oreo|Twinkie}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1996|author=w:Joel Spring|chapter=From Thomas Jefferson to Henry Ford: The End of the Choctaw Republic|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=APEvisJqs1oC&pg=PT214|title=The Cultural Transformation of A Native American Family and Its Tribe 1763–1995: A Basket of Apples|location=Abingdon, Oxfordshire&#59; New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Routledge|year_published=2011|section=part II (The Choctaw Republic and Its People)|doi=10.4324/9780203053614|isbn=978-0-8058-2303-5|passage=My ancestors five generations removed were \"'''apples'''\" who were \"White\" on the inside and \"Red\" on the outside. {{...}} We need a new breed of \"'''apples'''.\"}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1998|author=w:Opal J. Moore|chapter=‘From the Back of the Bus to the Back of the National Priority List’: The Civil Rights Movement, Integration, and beyond [Git that Gal a Red Dress: A Conversation Between Female Faculty at a State School in Virginia]|editor=w:Daryl Cumber Dance|title=Honey, Hush! An Anthology of African American Women’s Humor|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:W. W. Norton & Company|W[illiam] W[arder] Norton & Company]]|page=537|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/honeyhush00dary/page/537/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-393-04557-4|passage=The presenter, close to tears, told the audience that she's really an '''apple'''—white on the inside and red on the outside—Native American.}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col2|en|title=fruit of the genus ''Malus''\n|{{vern|cherry apple}} ({{taxfmt|Malus baccata|species}})|cooking apple|[[crab apple]], [[crabapple]] ({{taxfmt|Malus|genus}} spp.)\n|{{vern|dessert apple}}\n|eating apple\n|{{vern|wild apple}} ({{taxfmt|Malus|genus}} spp.)|wine apple\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|en\n| a bad tree does not yield good apples|acid of apples|Adam's apple|African custard apple|alley apple|[[alligator apple]] ({{taxlink|Annona glabra|species}})|American as apple pie|an apple a day,an apple a day keeps the doctor away,an apple a day keeps the doctor at bay|antiapple|applanche\n| Apple|appleade|[[apple aphid]], [[apple aphis]] ({{taxlink|Aphis pomi|species}})\n| [[apple banana]] ({{taxfmt|Musa acuminata|species}} × {{taxlink|Musa balbisiana|species}})|apple-bearing|[[apple bee]], [[apple-bee]] ({{taxlink|Bombus pomorum|species}})|[[appleberry]], [[apple-berry]], {{vern|apple berry}} ({{taxlink|Billardiera scandens|species}})|[[apple blight]] ({{taxlink|Erwinia amylovora|species}})|apple blossom|[[apple blossom weevil]] ({{taxlink|Anthonomus pomorum|species}})|apple bobbing|apples-to-oranges|apple borer|apple box,apple-box|apple brandy|{{vern|apple brown tortrix}} ({{taxlink|Pandemis heparana|species}})|{{vern|apple bud and leaf mite}} ({{taxlink|Phyllocoptes schlechtendali|species}})|{{vern|apple bud moth}} ({{taxlink|Spilonota ocellana|species}})|{{vern|apple bud weevil}} ({{taxlink|Anthonomus piri|species}})|{{vern|apple-bug}}|{{vern|apple bumblebee}} ({{taxlink|Bombus pomorum|species}})|apple bush,applebush|apple butter\n| apple cake|{{vern|apple canker}} ({{taxlink|Nectria galligena|species}})|apple cart,apple-cart,applecart|apple-catchers|apple charlotte|apple-cheeked|apple-cheese,apple cheese|apple cider|apple cider vinegar|{{vern|apple clearwing moth}} ({{taxlink|Synanthedon myopaeformis|species}})|apple core|apple-corer|applecrab|apple crook,apple-crook|apple crumble\n| appled|apple dandy|apple doll|apple domain|apple-domed|apple-dowdy|apple-drane,apple-drone|apple drops|apple dumpling|apple dumpling shop\n| apple-eating\n| apple-faced|apple-fallow|[[apple fly]] ({{taxfmt|Tephritidae|family}} spp., {{taxfmt|Drosophilidae|family}})| apple fries|apple fritter|{{vern|apple fruit weevil}}, {{vern|apple fruit rhynchites}} ({{taxlink|Rhynchites auratus|species}})\n| apple-garth|[[apple geranium]] ({{taxlink|Pelargonium odoratissimum|species}})|Apple Gifting Day|{{vern|apple grain aphid}} ({{taxlink|Rhopalosiphum fitchii|genus}})|{{vern|apple-grass aphid}} ({{taxlink|Rhopalosiphum insertum|species}})|[[apple grease]]|apple green,apple-green|apple-grey|{{vern|apple groundling}} ({{taxlink|Gelechia rhombella|species}})|applegrower|apple-gum\n| apple head,applehead|apple-headed|apple honey|applehood\n| apple ice wine|appleish|Apple Isle\n| apple-jack,applejack|apple jacks|apple jelly|apple jelly nodules|apple-john,applejohn|apple juice\n| apple-knocker\n| apple leaf midge|{{vern|apple leaf miner}} ({{taxlink|Lyonetia clerkella|species}})|appleless|applelicious|apple-like,applelike|apple liqueur\n| [[apple maggot]] ({{taxlink|Rhagoletis pomonella|species}})|apple mango|apple martini|[[apple midge]] ({{taxlink|Sciara mali|species}})|[[apple mint]], [[applemint]] ({{taxlink|Mentha rotundifolia|species}})|apple-monger,applemonger|[[apple moss]], {{vern|apple-moss}} ({{taxfmt|Bartramia|genus}} spp.)|apple moth,apple-moth|apple-mush\n| {{vern|apple nut}}\n| apple of Adam|apple of discord|apple of Grenada|apple of love|[[apple of one's eye]], [[apple of somebody's eye]]; [[apple of the eye]], [[apple of someone's eye]]|apple of Peru|apple of Sodom|apple-oil|apple orchard\n| apple pandowdy|[[apple pear]], [[apple-pear]] ({{taxfmt|Pyrus pyrifolia|species}})|apple-peeler|apple-peru|apple pie|apple pip|apple-plum|apple-polish|apple-polisher,apple polisher|apple-polishing|apple-pomice|apple potato bread|apple Punic|{{vern|apple pygmy moth}} ({{taxlink|Stigmella malella|species}})\n| apple red|applerita|Apple River|{{vern|apple root aphid}} ({{taxlink|Eriosoma lanigerum|species}})|apple rose|{{vern|apple rust}}|{{vern|apple rust mite}}\n| apples|[[apples and oranges]]|apples and pears|apple sauce,applesauce|{{vern|apple sawfly}} ({{taxlink|Hoplocampa testudinea|species}})|[[apple scab]] ({{taxlink|Venturia inaequalis|species}})|apple-scented mint|apple schnapps|apple-scoop,apple scoop|apple seed,appleseed|apple-shaped|{{vern|apple shell}} ({{taxfmt|Pomacea|genus}} and {{taxlink|Pila|genus|nomul=1}})|{{vern|apple small ermine moth}} ({{taxlink|Yponomeuta malinellus|species}})|apple-slump|[[apple snail]], [[apple-snail]] ({{taxfmt|Ampullariidae|family}} spp.)|apple snow|apples of gold|Apples of the Hesperides|apple sourpuss|apple's queen|apple-squire|apples to apples|apples to oranges|apple strudel|apple sucker|apple summer disease|apples with apples\n| appletini|[[Appletise]]; [[Appletiser]]|Appleton|apple tree|apple turnover|apple twig-cutter\n| apple up\n| {{w|Apple Valley}}\n| Apple Wassail|apple-water|apple wedger|[[apple weevil]] ({{taxlink|Anthonomus pomorum|species}})|apple-wife|apple wine|apple-woman,applewoman|applewood|[[apple worm]] ({{taxlink|Cydia pomonella|species}})|{{vern|applewort}} ({{taxfmt|Crataegus|genus}} spp.)\n| appley|apple-yard|Appleyard\n| a rotten apple spoils the barrel|as sure as God made little apples,sure as God made little apples\n| bad apple|bake-apple,bakeapple,baked-apple|baking apple|Baldwin apple|[[balsam apple]], [[balm apple]] ({{taxlink|Momordica balsamina|species}})|[[beach apple]] ({{taxlink|Hippomane mancinella|species}})|bell apple|bite at the apple,bite of the apple|[[bitter apple]] ({{taxfmt|Citrullus colocynthis|species}})|{{vern|black apple}} ({{taxlink|Pouteria australis|species}})|{{vern|blade apple}} ({{taxlink|Pereskia aculeata|species}})|bob for apples|bone apple tea|bone apple teeth|Bragi's apples|[[bush apple]] ({{taxlink|Pouteria australis|species}})\n| candied apple,candy apple|caramel apple|cashew apple|[[cedar apple]], [[cedar-apple rust]] ({{taxfmt|Gymnosporangium|genus}} spp.)|cherpumple|[[chess-apple]] ({{taxfmt|Sorbus torminalis|species}})|cider-apple|cockatoo apple|cocky apple|coconut apple|{{vern|common thorn apple}} ({{taxfmt|Datura stramonium|species}})|compare apples to apples|compare apples with apples|cranapple|Criterion apple|[[custard apple]] ({{taxfmt|Annona|genus}} app.)\n| Dead Sea apple,Dead-Sea apple|{{vern|desert thorn apple}}, {{vern|desert thorn-apple}} ({{taxlink|Datura discolor|species}})|[[devil's apple]] ({{taxfmt|Datura|genus}} spp.)\n| earth-apple,earthapple|egg apple|[[elephant apple]] ({{taxfmt|Dillenia|genus}} spp., etc.)|[[emu apple]]s {{taxlink|Kunzea pomifera|species}}; {{taxfmt|Owenia|genus}} spp.|English as apple pie|eye-apple\n| for sour apples|[[fountain apple moss]] ({{taxlink|Philonotis fontana|species}})\n| gallapple|ghost apple|[[golden apple]] ({{taxfmt|Aegle marmelos|species}})|grapple|{{vern|green apple aphid}} ({{taxlink|Aphis pomi|species}})\n| [[hedgeapple]], [[hedge apple]] ({